40|$|We {{estimate}} {{channels of}} international risk sharing between European Monetary Union (EMU), European Union, and other OECD countries 1992 - 2007. We focus on risk sharing through savings, factor <b>income</b> <b>flows,</b> and capital gains. Risk sharing through factor income and capital gains {{was close to}} zero before 1999 but has increased since then. Risk sharing from capital gains, at about 6 percent, is higher than risk sharing from factor <b>income</b> <b>flows</b> for European Union countries and OECD countries. Risk sharing from factor <b>income</b> <b>flows</b> is higher for Euro zone countries, at 14 percent, reflecting increased international asset and liability holdings in the Euro area. ...|$|R
