40|$|We examine if {{capital flows}} from states where total factor {{productivity}} is low to states where it is high. We do not observe interstate capital flows directly; however, suppliers of capital receive net factor <b>income</b> <b>flows</b> from other states and we can infer the direction of net factor <b>income</b> <b>flows</b> from {{the difference between the}} income received and the output produced in a state. We infer the relative level of {{total factor productivity}} from the relative level of output. The results are consistent with residents of states investing in states where total factor productivity is higher. The results also reveals that ownership patterns last over many decades...|$|R
40|$|The {{existing}} literature on inequality between {{private and public}} sectors focuses on cross-section differences in earnings levels. Forward-looking agents, however, care about income and job mobility too, which we show are substantially different between the two sectors. Using data from the BHPS, we estimate a model of income and employment dynamics, allowing for unobserved heterogeneity in the propensity to be employed in either job sector. We detect a positive average public premium both in <b>income</b> <b>flows</b> and in the present discounted sum of future <b>income</b> <b>flows.</b> We also find that income inequality is lower but more persistent in the public sector. Copyright 2007 The Author(s). Journal compilation Royal Economic Society 2007. ...|$|R
